questions.text: True regarding red areas of spleen is/are?
questions.solution: ACE Ref: Junquiera’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas, 14th Ed Explanation:Key points regarding the structure of spleen • The spleen is surrounded by a capsule of dense connective tissue from which emerge trabeculae, which partially subdivide the parenchyma or splenic pulp. • The splenic pulp has two components, the white pulp and the red pulp. 1. White pulp: a. There is a small central arteriole enveloped by a sheath of T lymphocytes, theperiarteriolar lymphoid sheath (PALS), which in turn is surrounded by a zone ofB-cells forming lymphoid follicles. b. Surrounding the lymphoid nodules is a marginal zone consisting of many blood sinuses and lymphoid tissue, having macrophages, lymphocytes and dendritic cells c. Plays an important role in the immunological activities of the spleen. 2. Red pulp: a. The red pulp is composed almost entirely of splenic cords (cords of bilroth) and venous sinusoids, with perisinusoidal macrophages. b. The splenic cords contain a network of reticular cells or reticular fibers that support T and B lymphocytes, macrophages, plasma cells, and many blood cells (erythrocytes,platelets, and granulocytes). c. The venous sinusoids ultimately drain into the tributaries of splenic vein. d. Stave cells are unusual elongated endothelial cells which line the splenic sinusoids, oriented in parallel with the sinusoid's blood flow. e. The red pulp deals with the culling action of senescent RBCs.

questions.text: All of the following is/are true regarding anatomy of the parotid gland except?
questions.solution: ACD Ref: BDC Vol III/6th Ed; page 106-111 Explanation: Option A: False. Parotid duct, also known as Stenson’s duct opens on the mucosa of inner cheek, opposite to the 2nd upper molar tooth (Not 3rd) Option B: True. The facial nerve divides the parotid gland into superficial and deep lobes. The lobes are joined by an isthmus of the glandular tissue. Option C: False. The deep lymph nodes are situated deep to the parotid capsule (not in the deep lobe). Remember that superficial lymph nodes are located in the superficial fascia. Option D: False. Facial artery does not traverse parotid gland, although retromandibular vein does. See the diagram (often repeated) Option E: True. Sensory supply to the parotid gland is derived from the auriculotemporal nerve, except for the parotid fascia and overlying skin, which are supplied by great auricular nerve (C2, C3). Extra edge points about parotid gland Ectodermal origin Largest salivary gland Capsule formed by the investing layer of deep cervical fascia Parotid duct pierces buccinator muscle Parasympathetic nerves are secretomotor and reach via auriculotemporal nerve The plane between superficial and deep lobe is called Patey’sfaciovenous plane and contains the nerves and veins, which has surgical relevance.

questions.text: Which among the following is/are true regarding anatomy of kidney?
questions.solution: BD Ref: BDC 6th Ed/Vol 2/Pg 313-314 Explanation: Option A: False. The upper pole of each kidney lies opposite T11 (Sometimes T12) and the lower pole lies opposite L3 vertebrae. Option B: True. The upper pole of both the kidneys is slightly medial and posteriorly oriented as compared to the lower pole. Option C: False. Nerve supply comes from the renal plexus derived from celiac plexus and contains sympathetic fibres from T10-L1. Option D: True. Each renal artery is a branch of abdominal aorta and divides into anterior and posterior divisions. The anterior division further divides into segmental arteries (anterior: upper and middle as well as inferior). The segmental arteries give rise to interlobar branches, further forming arcuate branches, which eventually form interlobular branches. Option E: False. Collecting Tubules are the first structure to collect the urine and enter the pyramid as Ducts of Bellini.

questions.text: Not true regarding anatomy of the penis is/are?
questions.solution: ABD Ref: BDC 6th Ed/Volume 2/p.400 Explanation: Penile anatomy Arterial supply: From internal pudendal artery (a branch of anterior division of the internal iliac artery) Dorsal artery of penis: Run between corpora cavernosa; supply the fibrous tissue around corpora and skin of penis Deep artery of penis: Run within the corpora cavernosa after piercing the crura, thus supply the erectile tissue in the body of penis Artery to bulb of penis: Bulbo-urethral artery, supplies posterior part of the corpus spongiosum and the cowper’s glands. Penile skin is supplied by the superficial and deep branches of the external pudendal artery. Venous drainage: Three venous systems Superficial system: Eventually forms a single superficial dorsal vein which drains into the left saphenous vein Intermediate system: Contains the emissary veins which drain into circumflex veins and the deep dorsal veins Deep system: The crural and the cavernosal veins, which eventually drain into the internal pudendal vein. Lymphatics: Body of penis drains into superficial inguinal LNs whereas those from the glans drain into deep inguinal LNs. Nerve supply: Somatic: Skin is supplied by pudendal nerve via dorsal nerve of penis and posterior scrotal nerve. A small area on the root by ilioinguinal nerve. Parasympathetic: Responsible for erection due to vasodilatation and derived from pelvic splanchnic nerves (nervierigentes; S2S3S4) Sympathetic: Responsible for ejaculation and derived from L1 segment via superior and inferior hypogastric plexus.

questions.text: Waldeyer’s inner ring component(s) include?
questions.solution: CDE Ref: BDC 6th Ed/Vol 3 Explanation: Waldeyer’s ring is a ring of lymphoid tissue present in the neck. questions.text: The term ‘Spring ligament’ is used for which of the following?
questions.solution: C Ref: Grey’s 41st Ed, Snell’s Clinical Anatomy 9th Ed/Pg. 507 Explanation: Plantar calcaneonavicular ligament Also known as Spring ligament It is a strong ligament which runs from the anterior margin of the sustentaculum tali to the inferior surface and tuberosity of the navicular bone. Its individual components are The superomedial ligament The intermedial (medioplantar) ligament The lateral (inferoplantar) ligament The superior surface of the ligament is covered with fibrocartilage and supports the head of the talus. This ligament contains a considerable amount of elastic fibers, so as to give elasticity to the arch and spring to the foot.

questions.text: When occlusion occurs at the 2nd part of axillary artery, which among the following anastomoses can maintain the blood flow?

Anastomosis around scapula which connect the 1st part of subclavian with 3rd part of axillary artery. I. Around body of scapula Suprascapular (branch of 1st part of subclavian). Deep branch of transverse cervical (branch of thyrocervical trunk from 1st part of subclavian). Circumflex scapular (branch of subscapular, which is a branch of 3rd part of axillary). II. On the acromion process Acromial branch of thoraco-acromial (branch of 2nd part of axillary) artery. Ascending branch ofposterior circumflex humeral (branch of 3rd part of axillary). questions.text: Structure derived from 1st pharyngeal arch
questions.solution: Correct Answer (D) Anterior belly of digastric. The first pharyngeal arch, also known as the mandibular arch, is crucial for the development of structures related to the jaw and mastication. It is innervated by the trigeminal nerve (CN V). The muscles derived from the first pharyngeal arch include the muscles of mastication (masseter, temporalis, medial pterygoid, and lateral pterygoid), the mylohyoid muscle, the tensor tympani, the tensor veli palatini, and the anterior belly of the digastric muscle. Now let's look at why the other options are incorrect: A. Levator palatini: The levator veli palatini muscle is derived from the fourth pharyngeal arch and is innervated by the Vagus nerve (CN X). B. Buccinator: The buccinator muscle is a muscle of facial expression and is derived from the second pharyngeal arch (hyoid arch), hence it is innervated by the Facial nerve (CN VII). C. Stylohyoid: The stylohyoid muscle is also derived from the second pharyngeal arch and is innervated by the Facial nerve (CN VII).
